  "prompt": "What would cause a demand curve to shift?",
  "response": "Several factors can cause a demand curve to shift:\n\n1. Changes in Income\n- For normal goods: Higher income increases demand\n- For inferior goods: Higher income decreases demand\n\n2. Price of Related Goods\n- Substitutes: If substitute good's price rises, demand increases\n- Complements: If complement good's price rises, demand decreases\n\n3. Consumer Preferences\n- Changing tastes or trends\n- Shifts in cultural or social attitudes\n- Marketing and advertising\n\n4. Population Changes\n- Population growth or decline\n- Demographics shifting\n- Age distribution changes\n\n5. Expectations\n- Anticipated future price changes\n- Expected future income changes\n- Economic forecasts\n\n6. Future Price Expectations\n- Expectations of future price increases might cause immediate demand increase\n- Expectations of price decreases might cause immediate demand decrease\n\n7. Seasonal Factors\n- Seasonal demand variations (e.g., winter coats, summer clothing)\n- Holiday-related consumption patterns\n\n8. External Shocks\n- Natural disasters\n- Political events\n- Technological innovations\n\n9. Changes in Government Policies\n- Taxes\n- Subsidies\n- Regulations\n\nThese factors can cause the entire demand curve to shift left (decrease) or right (increase), rather than moving along the existing curve.",
